{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"500d082a-29d2-4cc3-b326-f1551eb53b23","content":"Add a `.vscode/mcp.json` file to your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThis tells VS Code to launch your server via `dotnet run` and communicate over stdio. Make sure your server implements the MCP stdio transport (reads JSON-RPC from stdin, writes to stdout).\n\nIf you've already published a built binary, you can point `command` directly at the executable instead:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"command\": \"src/MyMcpServer/bin/Release/net8.0/MyMcpServer\"\n}\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"df7e3598-5d08-4cf3-9412-bc7b6335b53e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to know how to configure `mcp.json` to use their C# MCP server with GitHub Copilot in VS Code agent mode. Let me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge of VS Code MCP configuration.","outputTokens":269,"requestId":"C029:74DAE:1D3FBE1:20DC632:6A07C2D3"},"id":"3bbf512f-e45a-4e66-9ff9-6f3cdcb44be1","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:05:30.166Z","parentId":"80f13fc0-0716-497c-bced-2a5c5a1aaf73"}
